  "prompt": "Where can I find comedic monologues from published plays?",
  "response": "You can find comedic monologues from published plays through several resources:\n\n1. **Library Collections**: Many libraries have extensive collections of plays. You can check out anthologies of comedic plays or specific playwrights.\n\n2. **Online Databases**: Websites like JSTOR or Project MUSE may have access to play texts and academic papers that discuss them.\n\n3. **Play Publishing Companies**: Publishers like Samuel French, Dramatists Play Service, and Theatre Communications Group often have catalogs of plays. Their websites may provide excerpts or allow you to purchase the full text.\n\n4. **Monologue Books**: There are many books dedicated to monologues, such as \"The Best Men's Stage Monologues\" or \"The Best Women's Stage Monologues.\" These often include selections from published plays.\n\n5. **Theater Websites**: Websites like StageMilk or Monologue Archive offer a collection of monologues categorized by type, including comedic options.\n\n6. **YouTube Performances**: Watching performances of plays can sometimes help you identify great comedic monologues. Look for clips of productions or monologue performances.\n\n7. **Drama Schools**: Many drama schools publish resources for students, including monologue collections. Check their websites or ask for recommendations.\n\n8. **Online Retailers**: Websites like Amazon or Barnes & Noble often sell anthologies or individual play scripts that include comedic monologues.\n\nBy exploring these resources, you should be able to find a variety of comedic monologues suitable for auditions or performances.",
